<section xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="SendRedirects" version="5.0">
  <title xml:id="NetworkConfig">Disable Sending ICMP Redirects</title>
  <para>
  Prohibits the system from sending ICMP redirects.
  <indexterm><primary>ICMP</primary></indexterm>
 </para>
  <para>
  The ICMP protocol uses “redirect” messages to notify a traffic
  source regarding its suboptimal use of routing. Such a redirect is
  normally sent by the default router to the system to indicate that
  there is a shorter route to a particular destination.
 </para>
  <para>
  Allowing your system to send ICMP redirects is a security risk. It is
  recommended that you apply this module to prevent your system from
  being involved in denial-of-service attacks.
  <indexterm><primary>denial-of-service</primary></indexterm>
 </para>
  <table xml:id="table-prohibit-sending-icmp-redirects" frame="all" cellspacing="2" cellpadding="2" pgwide="1">
    <title>IP Settings to Prohibit the Sending of ICMP Redirects</title>
    <tgroup cols="3">
      <colspec colname="c1" colwidth="0.5*" align="left"/>
      <colspec colname="c2" colwidth="0.5*"/>
      <colspec colname="c3" colwidth="1.0*"/>
      <thead>
        <row>
          <entry>Operating Systems</entry>
          <entry>Configuration Files</entry>
          <entry>Setting</entry>
        </row>
      </thead>
      <tbody valign="middle">
        <row>
          <entry>Fedora 10, 11, 12, and 13</entry>
          <entry morerows="4">
            <filename>/etc/sysctl.conf</filename>
            <indexterm>
              <primary>/etc/sysctl.conf</primary>
            </indexterm>
            <indexterm>
              <primary>Files and Directories</primary>
              <secondary>/etc/sysctl.conf</secondary>
            </indexterm>
            <indexterm>
              <primary>sysctl.conf</primary>
            </indexterm>
          </entry>
          <entry morerows="4">
            <literallayout class="monospaced">
net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0
net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects = 0</literallayout>
            <indexterm>
              <primary>send_redirects</primary>
            </indexterm>
          </entry>
        </row>
        <row>
          <entry>Red Hat Enterprise Linux 4</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
          <entry>Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
          <entry>Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
          <entry>SUSE 10 and 11</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
          <entry>Solaris 10</entry>
          <entry>
            <filename>/etc/default/ndd</filename>
            <indexterm>
              <primary>/etc/default/ndd</primary>
            </indexterm>
            <indexterm>
              <primary>Files and Directories</primary>
              <secondary>/etc/default/ndd</secondary>
            </indexterm>
            <indexterm>
              <primary>ndd</primary>
            </indexterm>
            <indexterm>
              <primary>ip6_send_redirects</primary>
            </indexterm>
            <indexterm>
              <primary>ip_send_redirects</primary>
            </indexterm>
          </entry>
          <entry>
            <literallayout class="monospaced">ip_send_redirects=0
ip6_send_redirects=0</literallayout>
          </entry>
        </row>
      </tbody>
    </tgroup>
  </table>
  <para>
  See the <emphasis>Solaris Tunable Parameters Reference
  Manual</emphasis>
  <footnote><para>
    Sun Microsystems. <emphasis role="underline">Solaris Tunable
    Parameters Reference Manual</emphasis>. Santa Clara, CA: Sun
    Microsystems Press, 2005.
   </para></footnote>
  and the Linux kernel’s networking variables/parameters (in the
  <filename>ip-sysctl.txt</filename> file) for more information.
  <indexterm><primary>Kernel</primary></indexterm>
 </para>
